  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering is a serious criminal offense with significant penalties. Here are some key details:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties:\n- Potential prison sentences of up to 20 years\n- Substantial fines (often up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved)\n- Criminal forfeiture of assets involved in the transaction\n\n2. Specific Statutory Provisions:\n- Violations typically fall under 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 and \u00a7 1957\n- Penalties can vary based on specific circumstances and amount of money involved\n\n3. Additional Consequences:\n- Potential asset seizure\n- Potential civil penalties\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Potential immigration consequences for non-citizens\n\nThe exact penalties depend on specific factors like transaction amounts, intent, and whether the offense involves international or domestic transactions. Consulting a legal professional would provide the most accurate assessment for a specific situation.",
